==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Burglary
<hw>Bur"gla*ry</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Burglaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Fr. <er>Burglar</er>;
cf. LL. <ets>burglaria</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Breaking and
entering the dwelling house of another, in the nighttime, with intent to
commit a felony therein, whether the felonious purpose be accomplished
or not.</def> <rj><au>Wharton.</au> <au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ By statute law in some of the United States,
<xex>burglary</xex> includes the breaking with felonious intent into a
house by day as well as by night, and into other buildings than dwelling
houses. Various degrees of the crime are established.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

